Notes: 40-carbon intermediate in the biosynthesis of carotenoids => ignore it.

name: Phytofluene
Notes: colorless carotenoid found naturally in tomatoes and other vegetables. It is the second product of carotenoid biosynthesis => ignore.

name: Zeaxanthin
Notes: Zeaxanthin is one of the most common carotenoid alcohols found in nature. It is important in the xanthophyll cycle. Synthesized in plants and some micro-organisms, it is the pigment that gives paprika (made from bell peppers), corn, saffron, wolfberries, and many other plants and microbes their characteristic color. => ignore

name: Cryptoxanthin, beta
Notes: Cryptoxanthin is a natural carotenoid pigment => ignore.

name: Lutein
Notes: Lutein (/ˈljuːtiɪn, -tiːn/;[2] from Latin luteus meaning "yellow") is a xanthophyll and one of 600 known naturally occurring carotenoids. Lutein is synthesized only by plants, and like other xanthophylls is found in high quantities in green leafy vegetables such as spinach, kale and yellow carrots. => ignore

name: Lycopene
Notes: Although lycopene is chemically a carotene, it has no vitamin A activity. => ignore

name: Lutein + zeaxanthin
Notes: Combination of two components that are each ignored => ignore.

name: Tocopherol, beta
Notes: Tocopherols (/toʊˈkɒfəˌrɒl/;[1] TCP) are a class of organic chemical compounds (more precisely, various methylated phenols), many of which have vitamin E activity. => display vitamin E, do not display the Tocopherols
